<chapter subject="Chemistry" id="211" name="Organic Chemistry: Some Basic Principles and Techniques">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Organic chemistry is the study of ____ compounds.</text>
            <option id="A">Carbon</option><option id="B">Silicon</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Specifically hydrocarbons and their derivatives.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The first organic compound synthesized in the laboratory from an inorganic one was ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Urea</option><option id="B">Methane</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Synthesized by Wohler from Ammonium cyanate.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hybridization of carbon in Methane (CH4) is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">sp3</option><option id="B">sp2</option><option id="C">sp</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Tetrahedral geometry.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hybridization of carbon in Ethene (C2H4) is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">sp2</option><option id="B">sp3</option><option id="C">sp</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Trigonal planar geometry with a pi bond.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hybridization of carbon in Ethyne (C2H2) is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">sp</option><option id="B">sp2</option><option id="C">sp3</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Linear geometry with two pi bonds.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Bond angle in sp3 hybridized methane is ____ degrees.</text>
            <option id="A">109.5</option><option id="B">120</option><option id="C">180</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Perfect tetrahedral angle.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
